texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: ● Inconsistent Layout: Documents as PDFs often have inconsistent layout, which means that the content is positioned in a nondeterministic manner, making it hard to programmatically extract text, tables, or images in a way that retains the original meaning or structure.
texts.text: ● Inconsistent Layout: Documents as PDFs often have inconsistent layout, which means that the content is positioned in a nondeterministic manner, making it hard to programmatically extract text, tables, or images in a way that retains the original meaning or structure.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: ● Lack of Structural Metadata: PDFs frequently lack explicit structural metadata, such as headings, paragraphs, or the semantics of tables. This absence complicates the identification of different content types and the understanding of their hierarchy and interrelationships.
texts.text: ● Lack of Structural Metadata: PDFs frequently lack explicit structural metadata, such as headings, paragraphs, or the semantics of tables. This absence complicates the identification of different content types and the understanding of their hierarchy and interrelationships.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: ● Complex Layouts and Formats: Documents with multi-column layouts, footnotes, sidebars, or tables pose additional challenges. Typically, extraction tools may strip away context during the process, diminishing the usefulness of the data retrieved.
texts.text: ● Complex Layouts and Formats: Documents with multi-column layouts, footnotes, sidebars, or tables pose additional challenges. Typically, extraction tools may strip away context during the process, diminishing the usefulness of the data retrieved.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: ● Quality Issues: When dealing with scanned PDFs, the quality of the scan can significantly affect the ability to extract text. Poor quality scans may result in OCR errors, missing characters, or incorrect text, requiring manual correction or sophisticated error-handling algorithms.
texts.text: ● Quality Issues: When dealing with scanned PDFs, the quality of the scan can significantly affect the ability to extract text. Poor quality scans may result in OCR errors, missing characters, or incorrect text, requiring manual correction or sophisticated error-handling algorithms.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: ● Multimodal Content: PDFs can contain a mix of text, images, graphics, and sometimes even multimedia elements. Extracting data from these varied content types requires different approaches and technologies, complicating the extraction process.
texts.text: ● Multimodal Content: PDFs can contain a mix of text, images, graphics, and sometimes even multimedia elements. Extracting data from these varied content types requires different approaches and technologies, complicating the extraction process.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: ● Security Features & Encrypted Content: Some PDFs contain embedded or encrypted content, which can require additional steps to access and decode before extraction is possible. PDFs can have security settings that restrict copying, printing, or editing of the document. These features can prevent extraction tools from accessing the content unless appropriate permissions are provided or bypassed.
texts.text: ● Security Features & Encrypted Content: Some PDFs contain embedded or encrypted content, which can require additional steps to access and decode before extraction is possible. PDFs can have security settings that restrict copying, printing, or editing of the document. These features can prevent extraction tools from accessing the content unless appropriate permissions are provided or bypassed.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: PDFs don't store headings, paragraphs, or tables semantically-just positioned text/graphics.
texts.text: PDFs don't store headings, paragraphs, or tables semantically-just positioned text/graphics.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Content is stored as X-Y coordinates; there's no flow or DOM-like structure.
texts.text: Content is stored as X-Y coordinates; there's no flow or DOM-like structure.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Fonts may use custom encodings or missing glyph mappings (e.g. ligatures, symbol fonts).
texts.text: Fonts may use custom encodings or missing glyph mappings (e.g. ligatures, symbol fonts).

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Difficult to infer logical reading order across columns.
texts.text: Difficult to infer logical reading order across columns.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Text inside images needs OCR; images mixed with text confuse structure.
texts.text: Text inside images needs OCR; images mixed with text confuse structure.

table_cells.text: Not easily parsed-these are drawings, not data.
Tables might be represented as just spaced text (no lines/cells).
Lines split across rows (e.g. "informa-\ntion") must be intelligently rejoined.
Text at angles (e.g. vertical headers, rotated page scans) requires special handling.
Repeating noise across pages; must be removed to avoid duplication.
Must first convert image to text using OCR (adds noise, can misread).
OCR accuracy drops if the image is blurry, compressed, or skewed.
Often laid out as images or special fonts-hard to parse or understand.
Form fields are visual; mapping input areas to semantic labels is non-trivial.
Mixed languages, RTL scripts (e.g., Arabic), or special symbols are challenging.
Appear in content layer or separate annotation layer; hard to distinguish.
Some PDFs store pages out of logical order (e.g., booklet layouts).
